  "informal_statement": "Erdos #1052 (open): are there finitely many unitary perfect numbers? This packet proves only bounded companion infrastructure toward the known (Subbarao-Warren 1966) result that unitary perfect numbers are even -- NOT the open problem itself and NOT yet the full even_of_isUnitaryPerfect headline theorem. Continues frontier.erdos.erdos_1052_proper_eq_erase.v1: proves that in a unitary divisor d of n divisible by prime p, the full p-part of n divides d (ordProj_dvd_of_mem_uDiv), and that removing the full p-part of n from a divisor leaves a p-free quotient (not_dvd_div_ordProj, the root).",
  "informal_proof_idea": "ordProj_dvd_of_mem_uDiv: from d being a unitary divisor divisible by p, coprimality forces p to not divide n/d, so n/d's p-factorization is 0, giving n's p-factorization <= d's, hence ordProj[p] n = p^(n.factorization p) divides p^(d.factorization p) divides d. not_dvd_div_ordProj: by contradiction, if p also divided the quotient d / ordProj[p] n, then p^(n.factorization p + 1) would divide d, contradicting the factorization bound via Nat.Prime.pow_dvd_iff_le_factorization.",
  "formal_statement_pp": "theorem not_dvd_div_ordProj {n p d : ℕ} (hn : n ≠ 0) (hp : p.Prime) (hdvd : d ∣ n) (hPd : ordProj[p] n ∣ d) : ¬ p ∣ d / ordProj[p] n",
